description: Sit Start on the crack. Pull a big move to a crimp and work across the face to the arete on the left side of the boulder. Top out from there. Super cool movement for an easy problem.
Start right hand in a sidepull slot and left hand on a medium sized tooth feature.  Get your foot on and have at it.
location: Hot Stuff Camp Roof

description: Climb the large flake right of Slot Machine to a ledge.  Move into left crack for harder, cleaner finish or move right to bush whack to the top.  Good lead for 5.7, tricky gear.
Obvious chimney half way up the gully.  Several variations.  Expect to find scout troops camped out on this climb.
Vertical hand crack to the right of Stairway to Heaven.  Climb crack to overhanging off-width (crux).  Above is easy, dirty climbing to top.
Large off-width/squeeze chimney in the center of the wall.  Very polished as this is where every one seems to camp out.
protection: SR, there is a chock stone about half way up you can sling.

description: Diagonal hand crack that starts on the left side of the wall.  Joins the route A-Wall then tops out.  The wall above the crack is not able to be protected.
protection: SR, upper head wall not protected.

description: Vertical hand crack right of the diagonal crack Lefty and Poncho.  The crack disappears two thirds of the way up.  Continue on slopers and pockets to top.
protection: SR, mostly hand size.  Upper head wall is not able to be protected.

description: Start right hand jug sidepull in the crack and opposing left hand jug.  Hug your way to the end of the roof and pull the bulge to the topout.
location: Hot Stuff Camp Roof

description: Stand Start on the obvious side pulling jugs. Climb the face. Don't fall on your face.
Fierce microboulder. Sit start on the obvious jug on the detached block. Stay low to and work along the lip. Once you get to the horn, top er' out. The most fun you can have two feet off the ground.
location: Lip of the detached block next to the main boulder.

description: Short and powerful movement up the aerete. The opposing detached block is off.
location: Squat/stand start on two obvious crimps on the knifes edge

description: A kid on top of the boulder informed me that "its much easier to get on top from the other side".
location: Right up the middle of the tallest part.
Start matching on a crimp.
The crack and everything under it is off!
Don't bail left. Go straight up the face

description: Opening dyno followed by more long moves.
location: #3rd route on the left, to the right of Fat Chicks.

description: An easy 5.6 section to the left of a chossy arete leads you to a bulge and some hidden holds.
location: To the right of Monkey Spank.

description: Sit start below and left of the steep prow. Left hand is a flat jug, right hand is a two finger pocket. Move up and right to tackle the steepest part of the prow. Campus or heel hook to gain the upper slab. Sick movement on gorgeous stone.
location: Left-most, steep prow.

description: Right side of boulder. Starts as low as possible on a slot and a flat jug. Moves to two finger pockets out right and then pulls the bulge on great holds . The crux on this one is keeping your hips in and not dabbing on anything. Dab anything and you blow your send.
Technical and strength route. Start on small hold to a two figure pocket. Then to a left hand ledge. Go up to good pockets. Have fun.
location: Farthest right on T wall.

route_name: Sneaky D.L. Fingers on the Hush Hush
description: The crux is right off the ground. The first move is probably the hardest. The next 3 are still hard but become sequentially easier. The first few holds are wet, so bring a rag to dry them off. The route becomes significantly easier from there on up.
location: This is the left most route on the T Wall.
protection: I would highly recommend clipping at least the first 2 bolts before trying the route. It's an easy repel down, or you can stick clip them.

description: I couldn't find a definitive crux. I think this route offers some pretty amazing movement. Movement that I've never gotten the opportunity to do on any other route in Iowa. I also really enjoyed this route because I felt that it is not too strenuous on the fingers, but it requires full body engagement the whole way through. Thank you Troy Davison for taking the time to bolt this amazing line!
location: The route is the middle of the three routes on the T-Wall. The start is on the left of the bolt line.
protection: This route requires 5 bolts and the anchors. I recommend clipping the first 2 bolts to keep it safe and fun, as the landing could be bad if you don't. I also suggest brining a friend along who offers their full support. Thanks, James!

description: *Copied description from climbing.com**
"THE CLASSIC HARD BACKBONE CLIMB. Climb the thin crack to a dihedral (about 45 ft up). Stem the dihedral to a ledge. Top out on a hard hanging offwidth. (~70 feet)"
50' to the left of Devil's Hideaway (the one with the obvious roof).
protection: Trees near the top you can sling for anchors.

description: 25 feet right of Monster Crack. Climb the hand crack up to the large roof. Go left through the roof and the hold all but disapear.
location: Follow The Backbone Trail down to the west side and loop back to the bend in the river. There are several steep short cuts for a more adventurous trip to the bottom.
protection: Set top rope anchors from two trees directly above the route

description: lots of bad 2 finger pockets, the grade can be disputed.
location: 1st route on the left.

description: somewhat polished, grade is more consistant than Atropine
location: Left of atropine

description: From my observations, the difficulty of this climb is more consistent than Soul.
location: Route to the left of Soul Ignition.

description: Has one really tough move
location: One route left of Bird in Hand.

description: Route shares rap hangers with Wild Iowa.
location: 2nd route from the left, right of Wild Iowa.
protection: 2 bolts, rap hangers(same as Wild Iowa).

description: Make the clip on the second bolt, breathe and finish it.
location: Third from the right. Left of Virgin, crack and cave to the left.

description: Bouldery start on polished holds, pull a bulge and jugs to the top, pumpy.
location: Right of Bird in hand, first route left of Gotz Crack.
protection: 4 bolts(3 of which are spinners), rap hangers

description: Obvious crack that splits the face of Wild Iowa Wall. Sees little traffic.
location: The crack coming from the cave between Hot Tomale on  the left, and Hungry on the right.
protection: Gear, If top roping, there are trees on top for anchor, or climb Hungry or Hot Tamale and use their anchors to top rope.

route_name: Crack to the right of Atropine
description: Crack has some hand jams and each side has pockets and edges for easy hand and foot holds.  The ledge you take exiting the crack can be muddy.  There is little protection until you get from there to the tree.
location: This is the crack to the right of Atropine.
There is an easy walk-off to the left.

description: One of the more popular climbs on Wild Iowa Wall, steep pocket pulling!
location: 5th route from the left. From Gotz Crack second route to the right. Look for a good sized jug that has been epoxied back on.
protection: 3 bolts to rap hangers (the left hanger is a spinner)

description: short one or two move wonder, after the first bolt this is a 5.8
Alternate start aka "Atropine Direct"

Start to the left of the last two bolts, pull off a right hand on the bottom of the bulge to hit a left hand on the bulge and hit a bucket over the bulge, continue straight up to end just to the left of the anchors. Either stick clip the first bolt (because you can't reach it) or hang on till the second.
most climb the line starting under the first bolt going up over the bulge.
location: route farthest to the right.

route_name: Hollywood on a Buck O' Five
description: Around the corner is a lone vertical to slightly overhanging route. Climb the chossy bottom section to a ledge, past this the climbing is very high quality. May be the best 5.9 at Pictured.
location: Around the corner from the main wall.

description: Sharp and dirty.
location: To the right of Datura.

description: The first 20 feet are the crux. Top out on a ledge. Route goes vertical to slab, clipping the 3rd bolt can be a little hairy.
location: To the right of the main wall, Only bolted line on the face.
protection: 4 Bolts, Fixe anchors - There is a crack at the ledge that will take a tricam.

description: A few weird moves, some hidden holds. At least one poorly placed bolt.
location: left most route.

description: Link-up of Monkey Spank and Lesbian.
location: Unsure of how this starts.

description: Climbs up the arete. This route has seen more traffic as of fall of '07 possibly reducing the amount of loose rock.  More recently, Joe Stark and Troy Davidson have done some scaling work over the winter with the approval of the land managers to remove the dangerous choss (ie, loose rock) so that it is now a safe and worthwhile climb.
location: To the right of Lesbian Knife Fight.
protection: 7 bolts to a pair of rap rings.

description: Easy climbing on good holds, the crux is between the  third and fourth bolts requiring the climber to reach on not so good holds, great climb for the beginning leader or top roper.
location: First Climb you will see on Shiprock, farthest left of the three.

description: Starts off in the middle of the boulder with some big holds, then goes straight up to a dirty top out.
I cleaned off most of the lose holds, and dirt.  April '13
location: Middle of the "Razorblade Boulder"

description: Climb up and right on hand and fist jams to a dihedral.  Move up the dihedral to a ledge.  Climb left up a thin crack to a sketchy top out.
location: Just South of And Then She Fell.

description: Dirty lid it the usually dirty crack about halfway between Schoolio and the cave. Can be lead on gear but remember this is Iowa limestone. Can also be TR'ed off a tree. The main crack starts about 25 feet off the deck.
location: Obvious crack on the left about halfway between the Comic Gallery and the cave.

description: Named because of a fall taken by Evan Fales.
location: right most route.

description: This is a trad lead protected with Aliens (hence the name). It starts slightly left of a plumb line from the left-hand Jugular anchor and takes more or less a direct line to the anchors on Jugular. For those not into trad leads, it can be top-roped from the Jugular anchors for a little extra fun after doing that route.
protection: A selection of Aliens (tri-cams might also work well in some of the placements). Bolt anchors at the top.

description: Easiest route by the general assumption.
location: Middle route.

description: Loved or hated, Schoolio climbs the right corner of the Comic Gallery/Ice Cave Wall.
location: If Facing the Comic Gallery, it is the route on the right side corner.

description: Steepest of the three.
location: farthest left route.

description: Climbs a short vertical section, runs out on a slab to the anchors.
location: From the Ice Cave go up and around on the right side, only bolted line.

description: Climb a slab to a short roof with good holds.  A big move to a huge jug is required to move past the roof.  A few more moves brings you to the anchors.
location: This is the left hand route.
protection: Six bolts to fixed steel cleaning biners. Please DO NOT use the fixed biners for toptoping

description: Big holds on pretty bomber stone.  Slab to a ledge then pull a slight belly before tackling the upper headwall. Climbs right of the bolt line.
location: This is the right hand line.
protection: Five bolts to fixed steel cleaning biners. Please DO NOT use the fixed biners for toproping. 👍

description: Climb the dihedral chimney.  The climb earns its name.
location: 20 feet left of Glenoid's.

description: Hand to Fist size Crack widens to off-width with a tricky top out.
location: Northern most crack.

description: Climb the jam crack 35 feet to a ledge.  Bush whack to the top.
location: Crack left of Slimer.

description: Body jam your way up to a large chock stone.  Move deeper into the flake and squeeze through the top to easy but slick climbing above.
location: Large Flake 20 yards to the left of Herniated Disk.
protection: Big Bros, We led it on a #2 C4 just below the squeeze.

description: Climb the chimney moving deeper as you ascend.
location: Left of Temple of Doom

description: Sidepull sit-start under the three big pockets and go straight up using big pockets, small pockets, and sidepulls.
The crux is past the small pockets, almost at the top - transition from sidepull to sidepull.
location: 2 min walk from the parking lot at the Razorblade Wall (super-flat face, slightly overhung).
Slightly to the right of the center of the wall - look for the three big pockets.

description: Tallest trad route at PR! The crux is about 20ft off the ground. Great start following thinner crack. Pull over top of a ledge about 30ft up. Continue to follow crack left. Pull over short/ small overhang on great jugs. Follow crack to top on fun 5.6 climbing.
location: Located on Shiprock. The route is to the right of "Over The Counter"
protection: single rack: .3-#6. Alpine draws for rope drag. Set up top rope off trees.

description: First bolt is a bit high, easy climbing up to it. A few tricky moves getting up to the main face. For the most part good pockets on a mostly vertical face, a few bulges.
location: From Tarzan go down and to the right. Facing the wall this is the left route. First route to the right of Tarzan, to the left of Over the Counter.

description: The crux is between the first and second bolt, one tricky move. Butt bombs onto rocks/tree roots are possible. After the second bolt, great cruising on jugs. When you get to the big hueco stay to the right of it.
location: To the right of Somn Somn.

description: No info available.
location: Left of Gumby Deranged.
protection: 4 bolts, double set of ring anchors.

description: It will probably be a little dirty. Lots of crimps and sloping holds.
location: North Facing route.

Continue past Tarzan, up to the left. Go down, cross the gully, and continue onward. You will come to a wall with two large cracks. Squeeze thru the crack on the right and then cross one more gully. You will climb thru another tight spot, and then down the hill to the right is the belay ledge for Winged messenger.

fa: Troy Davison - equipped by Joe Stark
description: Scramble up past the smaller cave on the right to start. Steep route with big moves to good holds. Sustained.
location: Second route from the right.

description: some really good powerful pulling with a bit of choss at the bottom. A nice dyno move at the top protects the anchors
location: route on the left

description: Start as far back in the overhang section as possible.  Usually the furthest back is seeping with water.  Bring some Chalk to dry out a key thin rail that tends to be moist.  Work a cruxy, possibly inverted, sequence to climb out of the over hang onto nice jugs and Top out.  Until the top of the boulder is cleaned up a bit more you climb right back down to your pad for a descent.
location: This climb starts under the obvious overhanging end of the boulder.

description: Sit start with feet under boulder.  There is another smaller part of the over hang right of Moon Jelly top out. Start on a left hand 2-3 finger pocket with a right hand 1-2 finger pocket.  Nice little 3-4 move problem. Top out is mossy on sharp rock. Down climb to climbers left where moon jelly tops out.

fa: Nate Slaughter, Alberto Lacayo III - equipped by Joe Stark
description: Starts from the ground. Steer clear of the large vine and make your way up vertical terrain to a large belly. Have fun pulling past this one then skate the slab to the anchors.
location: Right-most route on the Chicago wall.

description: one funky move with hidden holds
location: route on the right

fa: Troy Davison - equipped by Alan Grau
description: Good holds through slightly overhanging terrain to a long, steep move at the anchors.
location: The left-most route on the Chicago wall.

description: Fun climb with good pockets past a few overhanging bulges.
location: To the right of Julie's Kiss. This climbs the center line of bolts on the belay ledge.

description: Short and pumpy, big ledges and jugs.
location: Back wall of the Comic Gallery, to the left of the cave. Only bolted line on the back wall.
protection: 4 bolts, bolted anchor with rap rings.

description: Overhung juggy, often dirty due to little traffic.
location: Right of He-Man, next route left of Taz.

description: short easy section to a short roof and bulge.
location: To the right of Super Fly, starts up on belay ledge. Climbs the left most route, shares first one or two bolts with Three Strikes.

description: Shares the first two bolts with Flash, then continues to the right of Flash to its own chains. One muddy pocket under the overhang.
location: Shares start with Flash, then moves right, Left of Skeletor.

description: Climbs the big overhanging bulge the whole way up. Super Classic jug haul.
location: Shares first two bolts with He Man, To the right of The Buddha. climbs the overhang on the left side of the Comic Gallery.
protection: 6 bolts, hangers. Last bolt before face is a spinner.

route_name: Exquze me, do you have any Grey Poupon?
description: Tends to have more sloppy pockets then Three Strikes, grade may not be as consistent through the whole route.
location: From the belay ledge, this takes the route on the far right, to the right of Three Strikes.

description: A little overgrown from low traffic, slightly overhanging.
location: To the left of Flash, starts with the first three bolts of Flash, then moves to the left.
protection: 7 bolts (first three shared with Flash), Fixe anchors.

parent_sector: Collin's wall aka Parking lot wall
description: slabby polished climb.
location: leftmost route.

parent_sector: Collin's wall aka Parking lot wall
description: Good first lead. Usually dirty.
location: Right of Collin's Crack. First bolt is up on a slab. If it is your first lead, will seem a lot higher then you want it.

parent_sector: Collin's wall aka Parking lot wall
description: Start left of young and the bold to the odd bolt up and to the left. work right to the Young's anchors.
protection: Bolts. Traverse below bulge to finish on Young and the Bold. Rather vegetated in the summer below bolt 1.

parent_sector: Collin's wall aka Parking lot wall
description: The obvious left facing dihedral. Usually top roped.
location: center route
protection: gear for the crack(tricams, tcus, cams up to a #2 camalot)will take as much or as little as you put in it, one bolt, and anchors

description: Goes up some very nice stone past a large flake before tackling a couple roofs then finishing on a slab.
location: This is the bolted route on the east side of Flying Buttress. Route is most easily accessed by the lower river trail as you hike past Ship Rock.

description: Start up to a ledge and your first clip. Power through the first crux and into interesting, body tension type moves and two more clips. Rest, then decide on powering through a second crux or firing to a bucket of an exit hold. Enjoyable route.
location: Second route from the left on the wall.

description: Vertical to slightly overhanging line on quality limestone.
location: This is the center line on the main wall.

description: Some odd moves.
location: Farthest left route.
protection: 4 bolts, open hanger and a chain for anchors.

description: One fun move.
location: Rightmost route on the main wall. To the left of For Gumbies Only.
protection: 2 bolts, rap hangers. Can use an orange or red tcu/equivalent alien in the horizontal, or tricam.

description: Climbs up the steep half-detached rock pillar. More like 5.7 if you stem and use the wall to the left.
location: farthest right, You will probably have to turn to the right to see this as you approach Gumby Wall.

description: One of the better climbs in PR, especially since the death flake was cleaned off in recent years.  Begin just a little left of the 1st bolt and enjoy technical pocket and crimps  through the bottom section to a good rest,  where the climb steepens. Look for the turtle head at the top of the pumpy bulge and keep cranking to the open cold shuts.
This climb can be damp at the horizontal and might be avoided if that area of the climb is wet/saturated.
The remnant of the death flake to the right should be avoided, that rock is choss and unstable.
location: Fourth route from the left, to the right of Ghost Dancer. There is a section of real junky rock in between this and ghost dancer.

description: Fun route on a variety of edges crimps rails... not just pockets, has had some large rocks pull off in the past.
location: First route on the left.

description: Big blank spot after the first bolt.
location: On the wall to the left of the main wall, it is the climb on the left.

description: Enjoy some big pockets up to the horizontal crack. Trust some less positive pockets on the arete near the top.
location: Up the right side of the nose of Dip Boulder, opposite Juggs Haul. Use both sides of the arete up top. Same start as Logan's Climb.

description: Future area classic, a true working man's boulder problem.

Start with your choice of either wide crack, or overhung tips crack (possibly harder than V0). Lieback your way up a couple of moves to buckets. Gain the keyhole. Rest up on a ledge large enough to bivy on and resist the temptation to escape onto the face to the left. Shuffle right until a gap wide enough for a well proportioned human appears above. Chimney up and out, crux is hip movement to leave the slot.
location: Directly right of the scooped face of the Dip Boulder. Hard to miss.
protection: Pads for the bottom, wide butt for the top.

description: Fall left into the mouth feature. Use technical feet to stay off the boulder to the left and ascend up shallow pockets on the face. Top out is not for the faint of heart.
location: Sit or stand start the nose of Dip Boulder where Juggs Haul begins. Go left immediately. Avoid the scary boulder to the left with hands and feet (and also while falling).
protection: 3 pads on ground, one on side boulder. Don't fall at the top. Seriously.

description: Start on the chest height jugs on the arete. Follow the crack feature up the left face, using good holds. Transition on to the right face and traverse right on the good lip, then top out to the left of the fallen tree. Top out is dirty/chossy.

Start low on a pretty nice start jug, work your way up the arete and stick the jug. Go left hand to the pinch above that and dead point or reach high to the obvious jug rail. Traverse the jug rail till you get to the end, then mantle or stem your way up to a chossy finish.
location: About 50 feet to the left of the Bay Wall.

description: Start low on the arete. Use jug holds and crack feature, head straight up to upper face. Pull over bulge on interesting holds. Crux is high
location: Arete left of scooped face on Dip Boulder
protection: Its tall, use a few pads

description: Navigate the blank face up to the bomber rail. Gain the top by finding the more reasonable honeycomb shaped features above the rail.
location: Start straight up the bowl shaped face between Logan's/Patrick's climbs and Slim Jim.
protection: 3 pads + spotter. Avoid the boulder back right.

description: Variation on Golden showers.
location: Starts to the right of Golden Showers, and meets up with it at the second bolt.

description: Short, little easy route on vert stone
location: Across from the wall with Blue Skies and Turn to Stone.

description: Long moves to an arm intensive clip of the anchors.
location: To the right of Happy Hooker.

description: The climb finishes on the same chains as Bad to the Bone.  Fun sustained climb.  The crux is clipping the chains.
location: Second from the left on the main wall.

description: Traverse, starting at Power surge and ending at Bone Yard.
location: Starts at the base of Power Surge.

description: Long moves on a steep roof, to a heel hook clipping stance for the anchors.
location: To the right of Gravity Amp and the left of Power surge.

description: The crux is clipping the bolt on the roof.
location: Sixth route from the left on the main wall.
protection: Bolts to shiny new chains, that are lower than the old rap hangers.

description: There is a pretty big dive on this climb if you miss the last bolt.
location: In between Deer Crossing and Today.
protection: Bolts to golden rap hangers, shares the first bolt with Deer Crossing.

description: Athletic moves on overhanging pocketed rock.
location: The fourth climb from the left.

description: The hangers are over the hump, so that they are hard to spot from the ground. Gets super crimpy at the third bolt.
location: To the right of Liberal Tendencies and to the left of Deer Crossing.

description: Starting from the ground, this is about 45' - four bolts to rap hangers.
location: First route right of Happy Toes traverse. Starts from the ground. Crux move pulling the bulge. Finish vertical to slab.

description: Clipping the first bolt.
location: To the left of the main wall, and perpendicular to it, it is the climb on the right.  Tends to be in the shade, so its climbed less.

description: Filthy, at times slabby.
location: Second climb to the right of the main wall.

description: Boulder problem start to great pocket pulling with fun, thoughtful and dynamic movement. Will probably require some brushing.
location: On a wall perpendicular to the main wall to the right.
protection: Three bolts to painted, chain anchors.

description: The crux is moving from the first to the second bolt.
location: Farthest left climb on the main wall.  This is generally a warm up climb. That said, it is the only one on the wall that doesn't get sunshine in the early morning, so it is a cold warm up.
protection: It is a bolted route with chains.

description: Its hard all the way up.
location: In between Today and Gravity Amp.
protection: Bolts to chains. Shares chains with
Golden Showers, Today, and Gravity amp.

description: Climbs the crack/groove/general weakness up to a chimney to the top.
location: 2nd route on the left, to the right of Hope. First move is probably the hardest of the whole route.

Descent: From the tree you used for an anchor go away from the cliff face and slightly to the right. You should see a gully going down to the right, this is an easy downclimb that will spit you out in the Comic Gallery. This gully can also be used to gain access to the top to rig a top rope for any of the climbs on A Wall.
protection: tricams, tcus/aliens, cams up to #2-#3 camalot the chimney could take bigger if you want to bring it up. Trees for an anchor.

description: Starts off slow. First three bolts are a few feet left of the rest of the route, I have seen the use of extended runners on these three bolts to decrease rope drag, although I think most people just use sport draws, as the rope drag is minimal.
location: Third route from the left. To the right of Herding Sheep.

description: It starts with 10 feet of easy slab up to a chossy seam where the first two bolts are placed. After passing the choss, it gets solid and you have to decide which great holds you want to haul on, till you get to a bulge at a seam just below the anchors. Pulling the bulge is the usual Iowa hunt for hands and feet, followed by clipping the anchors.  Except for the second bulge this is a stiff 10.
location: To the right of C N red is a shorter wall with a crack through the middle. This climb is the farthest right on that wall.

description: Start left of Doin the Smurf.  Ascend the mossy slab and get to the good rock.  Some nice pulling on smaller somewhat hidden holds leads to good jugs and then a crux at the top, traverse to the right to the shared anchors with Smurf.
location: Left of Doin the Smurf

description: There is a bulge between the second and third bolts that is balancy to pull.
Other than that, it is a pleasing jug haul.
location: Third climb from the right on the tall part of Boulevard wall.

description: Nice juggy climb.  Its probably closer to 5.10b in difficulty than to 5.11a, however the protection is sort of airy, so you probably don't want to try onsighting it unless you can climb 5.11 confidently.
location: On a wall to the right of the spearhead area facing it.
protection: Bolts to a chain anchor with quicklinks.

description: Pumpy moves on steep rock. Shared start with Boiler
Deceptively difficult with cruxes at second bolt and top.
location: Second from the left

description: The crux is getting on. After that you pull down hard on the obvious buckets, and hopefully have enough steam to finish.
location: This climb is in the middle of the Blue Groove. The Blue Groove is about 200 yards DOWN stream from Mother Wall on the same side of the river, tucked up high on the bluff. You will see two broken off pieces of limestone like spires just before you get there.

description: Titular route for the wall, it is steep and a little juggy like the rest.
Hard to find the holds at the bottom. The route transitions to move obvious sloped jugs as you go. Try not to get too pumped to clip the anchors.
The climb is too easy to have a crux, but if you climb it to the left, the holds are sort of slopey.
location: It is the feature that looks like a giant arrowhead that is visible up and to the left of the trail. There is a large collection of climbs on this wall.

description: Pulling the roof over the spearhead.
location: Starts to the right of the spearhead and then heads up and behind it coming out on a roof over the spearhead.  Don't blow the clip above the spearhead. :)

description: Easy slab into a gently overhanging face, which transitions into a roof.  Crux is pulling the roof, the approach, or the belay stance.
location: On its own wall south of Boneless Chicken Ranch.  Scramble up the steep slope and around a small, chossy boulder.  Belay ledge is a small 2' x 5' dirt pile.

description: The crux is a long move between the third and fourth bolts. The climb has a couple fun moves.
location: About 10 feet to the left of the spearhead.

description: Short and bouldery, the crux is an undercling, up and to the right of the third bolt.
location: This is the farthest left climb near the Spearhead, it is on the corner where the rock face turns, about 15 feet to the left of Flavor Blasted Spermacide.

description: A waste of bolts.
location: To the right of "Between the Sheets". It follows big jugs over a bulge to a point underneath the roof.  There is a continuation over the roof, that is about 5.10c, but is sparsely bolted to the anchors.

description: Somewhat hidden holds at one point.
location: Just to the right of In Through the Outhole is goes up just avoiding the roof over the spearhead.

description: The crux is pulling the bulge.
location: To the right of Talent Show but facing the trail instead of the Spearhead.

description: Seems hard
location: Fourth route from the right on the tall part of the wall that faces the trail. Just to the left of
Ward Off

description: There are two cruxes. The first is a small roof about 15 feet up. Actually the hard part is clipping the bolt above this. Next about 2/3's of the way up there is blank spot, that if you want you can avoid by climbing to one side of it.    Its not as sustained, or fun as Ward Off.
It does however have a plentiful supply of loose things that can fall on your belayer.
location: Second climb from the right on Boulevard wall, just to the left of
Go Left.

description: This climb really has no redeeming value.  It goes into a dirty chimney with lots of loose rocks for a few feet before it tops out at the anchors for Drillin' Hoes.  If you decide to do it, count to ten and think about it some more. Eventually, the urge will pass.
location: Starts at the left end of the right hand part of Boulevard wall and ends on the right hand side of the left part of Boulevard wall.

description: Chossy for the first 50 feet with a minicrux about 25 feet up.  The chossy minicrux can be avoided...
by going left ( a couple feet ) to solid rock with a couple of hard to spot bomber holds.
The fun starts for the last 10 feet where it is overhanging and juggy.
location: This is the furthest right climb on Boulevard wall.
Boulevard wall is further up the trail from the spearhead area. It is a pretty tall wall with some staining on it.

description: Crimpfest on a roof.
location: To the left of the main part of Boulevard wall, at right angles, there are three really hard climbs.
This is the middle one.

description: Starts on a horizontal roof to steep pockets.
location: This is the leftmost route on the left hand side of Boulevard wall.

description: The climb has two cruxes. The first is the start which is bouldery. The second is a crimpy sequence at the third bolt.
location: The route is at Motherwall, which is to the right of a prominant arch on the other side of the river about 200 yards up river from Boulevard wall. It has a vein of sandstone running through the limestone.

description: Horizontal roof to steep pockets.
location: Rightmost route on the left part of Boulevard wall.
Shares anchors with that horrible chimney route.

description: 3 stars for being a nice warm up on mellow jugs low to the ground. Start far right sitting down and work your way left and up to the center of the wall.
Starts very low, STD, with left hand on small nub and right hand in a sloper under-cling. Move up nice pockets and compression side pulls to the lip of the prow. Top out.
location: Top out should get better as time goes on.  Tread carefully or opt out of a true ascent and walk off left.

description: Start 2-3 feet right of the tree ( facing project boulder).  Climb up the slab shooting for pockets on the left side up under the mini roof, skeet left to get over the roof then head up a little right again to top it out.
protection: multiple pads.  Gets the R rating because if you fall you will most definitely hit the tree on your way down.

description: This climb offers some rare interesting movement relative to everything else in the area.  Start as low as possible perhaps using a back step and a toe hook under the gunky boulder along with a very low under-cling.  Immediately move up to some obvious crimps,then using scrunched up tricky foot work, work your way to the top.  Like most climbs here, the top is a path for run off water made obvious by the neat looking streak, so you may need to clean the top out jugs once per year and remove any build up.
Sit start on the right side of the Morell boulder.  Move up and top out on the right side of the boulder.
location: Right side of the Morell boulder

description: Start below a crack on the left side of the boulder.  Climb  up through the crack at the top, topping out on the left side of the boulder.
location: Sit start on the left side of the Morell boulder.

description: This climb is short but packs a punch for the climber working into the V3/V4 range. It starts at the bottom on some obvious holds .  Left hand works its way up the arete while right hand throws to a seemingly "great" pocket.  If you land this move the climb is over and goes right up the face.
location: Walk past Project Boulder around the corner and its the boulder right after LP Boulder.
protection: two pads, maybe a dab pad for the wall

description: Start as low as possible on good holds, use whatever means necessary to make your way up to the Tooth and Top out.  There are some not so obvious hidden jugs and multiple variations for getting up this climb.
location: In between Bae wall and LP

description: Starts in the middle of project boulder and climbs up towards the center using a right hand rail to get to a left hand crimp positioned in the center of the wall before the overhang starts. From here start to move right reaching up to a small left hand two finger side pull.  Throw right up and over the roof to find a juicy rail.  One more move to a deep pocket and walk your feet up over the roof and continue climbing a slabby section for another 6 feet to top.
Barbed Wire boulder is off as well as chossy looking stuff on right before over hang.

Start on the left side of the main face of Project Boulder. Use similar beginning holds as Welcome to Gumby Town. Go right along the pockets on the left side of the roof. Use the thin rail and shallow pockets to stick the jug at the prow. Don't blow the topout!
location: Left direct line on the roof of the Project Boulder.
protection: There are a couple large rocks near the back of the landing zone. 3-4 Pads plus 2 spotters is ideal if you don't want an oardeal while you're working the last couple moves.

description: Sit start on 2 small crimps in the middle of the boulder.  Climb straight up through the mini-roof, topping out at the highest point of the boulder.
location: Sit start in the middle of the boulder.

description: Starts matched on the chest-high horizontal pocket on the left of the bulge. Throw left and up for some smaller crimpy pockets before tossing big into the moss on the face of the slab. Head straight up, avoid the holds out right and leaving the moss (c'mon, you're barely 15ft up!) Good jugs and pinches to be had up into the roof, so calm down and forget you're standing in moss. Get some high feet and go for the bomber baseball-sized jug on top just left of the prow, (about 6 inches farther than you want it.) Take a deep breath and mantle the thing. Don't forget to look down and notice you are pretty stinkin' high for a boulder problem.
Named for the fact that the boulder itself looks like a human heart AND that the moss on the left of the slab face looks like a half of a heart symbol.
location: Climbs the straightest route directly up the slab face through the moss. Starts 4ft to the left of the R-rated tree from Gumbytown. Walkoff is the recently cleaned class 4 scramble to the right past the large cedar when you topout.
protection: 2 pads and 2 spotters preferable.The landing zone has a pointed rock that does a good job as a backstop for the second. Don't commit to the mantle topout if you don't have well trained spotters– traverse right onto easier holds and up through the gunsight instead.

description: Feels natural, but definitely also a little contrived. That's what bouldering is all about! Start by stepping on the slab and going up left hand to a good pocket. Your hands should always stay on the more blank vertical face until you near the top. The picture will make it more understandable.

Start as low as possible on jugs with a gaston/undercling combo.  Make a couple moves up to nice jugs and pull the bulge to a slab.  Crux is first few moves and pulling the bulge. Just a few moves and this one is done. Walk off to the left
location: Far left of the wall.

description: Start low nice rails or standing and move to crimp side pull and two finger pocket, move up through a disguising sea of moss to find decent pockets all the way up to a series of knobs and rails for top out.
location: This is one of those typical joinerville honeycomb looking climbs with thin limestone and small nuggets that tend to break off.  Be cautious which holds you grab and where you place your feet.  Hopefully with time and more traffic there will be less moss and better rock.
protection: A few Pads and a spotter

description: Sit down start as low as possible on questionable looking rock.  Move into the obvious crack and traverse up the arête towards the prow. Top out all the way to the top through the jungle of crap or opt out and walk off left on the slab.
location: It does Top out but rock is questionable so tread carefully.  Feel Free to Help clean on your way up!

description: Sit down start far right , move to jugs and climb up to nice top out rail.  Easy Climbing.
location: Far right of right side

description: Starts Left hand in an amazing side pull, right hand on a sloped face. Move right to a nice pocket with a sharp lip and work your way straight up just left of the prow .  Crux is reaching over the bulge to good holds. May be easier for taller climbers!  Not sure if it is 4 star worthy but it is really fun once you figure out the beta.
location: Walk off left on slab

description: Sit down start, left hand on 2-3 finger positive sloper, right hand on full hand sloper.  Move up to jug then follow the line of crimps which take you slightly right and up .  Massive undercling used on Boog's Big Dig is off.  Tops out either right and around the giant block going into poor quality honeycomb featured rock. I might have given it three stars if the top out wasnt so choss infested.  The movement and crimpy holds make for really good climbing.
location: Right side of Lower boulder
protection: a Couple Crash pads, maybe a dab mat for the rock to your back as your make your way up and right.

description: SD Start left hand on crimp side pull, right hand on lower crimp, Move to Jugs and top out highest point on the wall or bail to the left.
location: Slightly right of center

description: Start low on jug and side pull, climb straight up on surf like side pulls to a large rail
location: Far right on upper boulder

description: Start Low and Far left, Work your way right on jugs and side pulls towards the center of the boulder .
location: Left side of Lower Boulder

description: The crux involves utilizing a toe hook-heel hook compression move to get your right hand over and up on a better hold.  Some very fun and different movement relative to the redundant pocketed limestone found in the area.
Just like the Boulder's Description, this specific side of it is usually moist, mossy  and muddy during the spring and summer.  If you find it on a dry day, you should not pass this climb up.
location: Start with both hands matched as far back as you can get in the cave on a large low placed jug.  move left using 2 finger side pulls and slopers which eventually lead you up and over for the top out.  You can walk over to where CCB and MBB meet for an easy scramble down back to your pads.

description: Start as low as possible with left hand on left side and right and on right side of arete.  Climb up and good holds to a fun and easy top out.
location: This is to the left of merky bottom boys and climbs up the corner.

description: Sit start on the left side of the crack.  Move up and left, finishing on the arête.
location: Sit start on the left side of the crack.

description: Sit start in the middle of the furniture boulder. Hard start move to better holds.
location: Middle of the furniture boulder.

description: Sit start on good edges.  Move straight up to good holds and top out.
location: Left side of the boulder.

description: Sit start on the right side of the furniture boulder.  Good holds to a slopey topout.
location: Right side of furniture boulder.

description: Stand start on the far left side of the furniture boulder.  Traverse the boulder from left to right.
location: Starts on the left side of the furniture boulder

description: Sit start on the arête at the far right side of the boulder. Start with one hand on each side of the arête and climb straight up the arête.
location: Sit start below the arête on the right side of the boulder.

description: The bulge is somewhat barren, but try not to cheat on the routes to either side! Trust the crack up high to finish it off.
location: Just left of the Exams. Start on the bulge. Small pockets and technical feet low lead into the crack up above.
protection: 3 pads and a spotter. The topout has been cleaned out so its good, but the fall zone is sloped away.

description: Sit start 5 feet left of the arête, climb straight up on good holds.  Steep climbing on good holds.
location: Sit start 5 feet to the left of the arête.

description: Sit start below the tallest line in the middle of the boulder.  Climb straight up and top out finishing slightly to the right. Uses a sharp crimp at the crux.
location: Sit start below the tallest line in the middle of the boulder.  Shares the start with Entrance Exam.

description: Although tall and scary looking, this is a classic high ball and feels very secure on every move.  I was surprised how many times I had walked past this one before climbing it to find it was one of the best jug halls in the park.

Sit start for extra or just start on the big pocket center face.  Work your way up to nice juggy knob. The crux is pulling off of this knob and moving past the "do not fall" zone to a deep pocket and then up and over the top out.
location: This climb is between "Too Much Adderall" and "Entrance Exam".  The start is almost the same start as "Too Much Adderall' and branches right into a jug then straight up the face.

description: Same start as Final Exam, but bail out left at the top, avoiding the crux of final exam.
location: Shares start with Final Exam. Sit start below the tallest point in the middle of the boulder.

description: Sit start just left of the arête, climb straight up just to the left of the arête. Good holds on steep rock, fun problem.
location: Sit start a few feet to the left of the arête on the right side of the boulder.

description: Start in the hueco on the far right of the Freshman Boulder and traverse left, transitioning onto Community College Boulder. Avoid using the seam along the bottom for an added challenge. Finish in the hueco on the far left.
location: Straight up the access trail. Extends the full length of Freshman and Community College Boulders.
protection: One or more pads, and a spotter to move them

description: Sit start using an undercling.  Move straight up on mostly good holds to the topout.
location: Sit start in the middle of the right hand side of the Freshman boulder.

description: Sit start on good holds on the far left side of the boulder.  You start sitting on a small ledge.  Move right and then up for the finish.
location: Far left side of the boulder. Sit start up on a ledge.

description: Sit start on the right side of the crack, move up and slightly to the left.
location: Site start on the right side of the crack.

description: Start on Grounded (sit start).  Traverse all the way to the furniture boulder (trying not to scratch your butt on the tree as you transition onto the furniture boulder) and top out on Love Sac.
location: Shares start with Grounded on the far left side of the boulder.

description: Climbs the most center section of the face, slightly to the left of the distinguished tree above.  Lots of mud towards the top out if not cleaned.  Bomber jugs all the way on decent quality rock.

the crux in all the way from the start to the top out. site down start with two finger mono and right hand small crimp above move out to two holds right together. either go straight up or get the hold slightly higher left and then up for the top out.. also feet start is different find the drop knee and the start hold for the other climb is on if needed but nothing more to the left is on.
location: back  in the cave on the right side
protection: need at least one pad maybe two

description: start with big jug bottom right on wall. move up and to the right of the arete . match left and and foot go up on the left side and top out.
location: right side of wall this is a sit or lay start.
protection: two pads one on back wall and one right of your head for start.

description: Start on obvious holds center of face below a cut out in the top of the face.  move up using holds on left and right to a top out jug. Bring your feet up and either walk off left towards carpet shag top out on a slippery traverse or move up for a direct top out
location: Center face of Community College Boulder, right of carpet shag.
protection: pads and spotter,  PG13 because if you fall you will most likely hit the tree to your back or your spotter.

description: Sit Start and work your way up using fun face holds all the way to the top.
location: to the left of kickin it.

description: Sit start on the arête of the block. Goes straight up and tops out.
location: On the arete of the barbed wire boulder.

description: Sit start.   Climbs the face in the middle of the cove boulder on the right side of the arête.
location: In the middle of the face on the right side of the Alcove boulder.

description: Slab to steep pulling
location: Second route from the left on the wall at the top of the approach trail.

description: Long moves to small pockets on steep stone. Changes to vert at the top.
location: From the top of the approach trail go left and walk along the wall for approximately 50 yards until you come upon a wall with three routes. There is a large flake resting against a tree in front of this wall. This is the middle route.
protection: 4 bolts to anchors at the top with leaver biners.

description: Tough start through some choss, then the angle increases as the stone turns bullet.
location: From the top of the approach trail go left and walk along the wall for approximately 50 yards until you come upon a wall with three routes. There is a large flake resting against a tree in front of this wall. This is the rightmost of the three routes.

fa: Unknown - Probably Raud as he was scoping out Jealous
description: Did you get psyched on the beautiful high quality Jealous line and roll up to the crag alone with one pad only to realize your not up for committing to the high ball bad landing fall that is sure to ensue?  Well your effort was not wasted.  A little tamer in difficulty and grade, this may be your next best bet.  Depending on whether you sit start or stand start the grade can feel anywhere from V0 to V2.  Climb up the top corner of the face on decent pockets or move all the way into the jug filled crack and top out in the same spot as Jealous.
location: Located on the Jealous Boulder

description: Pulls the wave-like bulge. Stays tough at the top.
location: Leftmost route at 187

description: Climb the slab past two bolts to a ledge. A hard crux right off the ledge leads to easier climbing.
location: From the top of the approach trail turn left and walk to twenty yards to the next section of wall. There are two routes here; this is the righthand route.

description: Slab to steep pulling.
location: First route on the right on the wall at the top of the approach trail.

description: Start at the bottom left of the boulder on some underclings and move toward the prow for the finish. Sustained moves from bottom to top. Looks very hard from a distance. Look closely and you'll find everything you need is right there. I'm surprised a line/face like this exists in Iowa.
location: Right off the trail near the 187 Wall. You can't miss it. Down climb the easy crack on the left of the boulder.

description: Sustained movement throughout the entire problem. Classic roof climbing movement. Reminds me  bit of some bouldering down in Cowell, Arkansas
location: 50 feet to the right of "Jealous" near the 187 wall. Take a left on a trail that leads up to a cave. The route starts on the right of the cave on an obvious big jug.

description: Slab to steep jugs
location: From the top of the approach trail turn left and walk to twenty yards to the next section of wall. There are two routes here; this is the lefthand route.

fa: M. Black, equipped by Alan Grau
description: Climb up easy slab to better rock where the wall starts to slightly overhang then move left along the bolt line to pull a fun bouldery bulge sequence .  After the bulge, clip one more bolt to the anchors up left. Use an extended draw down low to avoid rope drag.  Everything on this route is OK for the capable 10d climber but pulling the bulge feels stout.  Thank you to Alan G. and other developers for bolting this line and the others surrounding.
location: Left of The Yin.

description: Sit start just right of the arête.  Climb up and right, using only the crack for your hands.
location: Stand start in the undercling crack on the right side of the Alcove boulder arête.

description: Sit start just to the right of the arête. Climb up through the swiss cheese looking rock at the top.  If you are a bad hold, keep looking, there is a good hold nearby.   Some of the holds are a bit sharp.
location: Sit start on good holds just to the right of the arête on the Alcove boulder.

description: Sit start below the crack 10 feet right of the arête.  Climb straight up roughly following the crack. Fun climb now that the thorn bush protecting the topout is gone.
location: Sit start 10 feet right of the arête.

description: Starts in obvious pockets, center of face, then climbs left (right of tree).  At roof shoot right hand up to one hell of a hueco, work your feet up to pull the roof with a final daring foot and stand up .  You have completed the first 15 ft, now continue to scramble on v-easy climbing to the top. walk off is left towards LP Wall
the tree is off.
protection: A good amount of crash pads.

description: See photo.
location: On the Bae Wall, start with 2 hand holds with obvious white striped markings.

description: Fun two handed dyno! Use the lower holds of Bae wall direct to jump to the scoop at the top of the beginning of the roof instead of heading into the crack.
protection: A few pads easy to swing out

description: The top of Bae Wall was cleaned off to allow the direct line on the Bae wall to be done. Use the two pockets where the face and the bottom of the roof meet before pulling through some washed out bowls above. Celebrate when you find the huge rail a few feet above the roof.
location: Direct line on the Bae Wall. Follow directions in the area description

description: Slightly overhung right side of Arete on Barbed wire boulder. Sit Start with left hand pocket and right hand low. Bump your hands up along smooth pockets to the top.
Sit start down low and work your way up jugs to a nice thread.  Tops out left.  Plenty of options for holds.
location: Furthest left problem on the boulder.

description: Start far right on great holds and use fancy foot work to traverse left towards the bulge.  Utilize different methods to pulling over the bulge and up left to top out.  "Still dirty but should clean up with time."  If someone hasn't climbed this one in a while it will need some serious gardening much like most of the climbs at JV.
location: Bulb like boulder on the right side of Ecosystems Area

description: This is an obvious, huge corner or chimney that should be unmistakeable and can serve as a reference point for routes to the left or right.
protection: Small to medium cams or chocks.

description: A lightning bolt shaped, fairly clean splitter crack / dihedral which is unique for the state.
Starts at #2/#3's and continues to widen as it goes up.
location: This route is most easily accessible by kayak/canoe.
Via boat: Drive on Kepler Drive north along the river, and park at the trailhead for the Cedar River Trail.
Row up river northwest, passing by large rock walls on the banks of the west side of the river on your left.
This crack should be visible from the river on one the rock faces set back further into the woods.

description: Short crack overlooking the river.  Starts off with some hands to fists and ends with offwidth near top.

As paraphrased from the Ferguson guidebook, the start to this climb is just to the right of a small pocket about four feet high.  Work up straight up to the top.  The crux is working over the ceiling about 15 feet off the ground.
protection: There's a decent sized cedar tree at the top.  Trad placements are pretty sparse.

description: Lead the crack on the right side of the arch.

Its pretty crumbly, and then exit it with a jug to the right of the crack which is usually muddy.  You want to put in a lot of gear before you make the crux move, and make sure that your belayer isn't going to get kabonged with the rock you knock loose.
location: This is the crack that goes up the right side of the arch.
protection: tricams, and cams. Set a sling on the tree that is centered over the arch.

description: Sit start with hands matched on the ledge under the bulge.  Bump left hand up a couple of times, then pull through the crux - getting the right hand up into a pocket.  Work your feet up high and find some pretty good jugs for a gentle top out.
3ft right of Sugar Rush is a little jug crack. Start here and move left on jugs to finish on Sugar Rush
location: Right of cave, right of Sugar Rush

fa: Dan Olsen, Tim Olsen, Russ Lee
description: Use your head in preparation for the classic crux move in the overhanging choss chimney.  We'll climb it again if you lead.  First ascent: Nordic Fest weekend 1977.
location: To reach the start, rappel into the gap between the bluff and free-standing pillar at the more southerly of the two Chimney Rocks.  Return carefully from climb.  A Tyrolean traverse has been used for this purpose, but is not really worth the fuss.
protection: Original ascent involved the arduous placement of a couple small pieces and a futilely marginal piton at the crux; to bolster false confidence and prolong a sense of terror.

description: Slap right of Diabeetus
location: Slab 10 ft right of cave

description: Dubuque routes submitted are star rated in relation to each other.
This over-hanging crack route seemed like it had seen previous action, perhaps even chalk remnants.

It is a short route but overhung and doesn't give up until overcoming the top roof.  Crux would be the top roof.  Good quality limestone minus the hanging chunk in the middle of the crack.  Be wary of this chunk, bits and pieces pull off easily but on the whole it feels sound.
location: Walk in on the lower Mines of Spain trail and spot the big outcropping within a 1/2 mile off to the left (north).
protection: We TRed but it would eat up great pro from a standard rack (maybe double up on 1"-3" pieces).  Tape might be a good idea for the bomber hand-fist jams.

description: Commit!!!!
Compresssss
BEep boop bap!
Start on the rail (green), the two extra foot holds are in pink. Finish on the red.
IT'S CLASSIC BITCH!
Start at far pocket and rail. Move to pocket and then to juggy rail to the left, then finish at top. One foot marked in photo, and then the whole left pillar.
location: B boulder

description: One move wonder-ful
Sorry shrimp. You're in the big kids playground now. Now give me all your lunch money before I sock you back to yesterday!
Good bouldering!
It's all good on this one.
techy but good feet!
Beautiful. Can't believe this rock exists in Iowa.
Same start and first 3 or 4 moves on Sugar Daddy then move right to finish on the jugs of Sugar Baby
location: Middle of the cave, same start as Sugar Daddy

description: Sit down and make a couple fun moves
location: Right of Zero Sugar and the down log

description: Right of Sugar Bear. Start on a small ledge crimp or open hand holds inches above, make a big move to a positive rounded jug, finish straight up
location: Right of Sugar Bear

description: Link up of Sugar Baby and Sugar Daddy.

Start on Sugar Baby, the obvious jug just above head level on the right side of the cave (your right if facing the cave). Make the first two moves of Sugar Baby then keep bumping left to the crimps on Sugar Daddy and finish straight up.
location: Link up of Sugar Baby and Sugar Daddy

description: Start in the cave left hand on the cave wall and right hand on a good hold on the roof (or both on the cave wall - whatever floats your boat).  Move through the roof on good holds to the stand start of Sugar Daddy.
The holds linking to the stand start are often wet, but with good conditions, this line is stellar. Bring a towel if you're working this problem.
Starts in the middle of the cave on two crimps and goes straight up. The is the first two moves, remains hard and committing to the top
location: Middle of the cave

description: Start on 2 underclings on the ramp, left side if the cave (your left when facing the cave). R hand up to the crimp next to the pinch of Creme Brulle. L hand to a crimp then throw for the small ledge up Left. Finish on slopers and crimps. Top out is a little scary but not crazy.
location: Just right of Sugar Tits. Finishes on small dihedral at the top.

description: Start on same jug as Sugar Baby. Climb straight up into a black bear looking feature to the top
location: Right side of cave

description: Start on the obvious jug just above head level on the right side of the cave (your right when facing the cave). Move left to a pinch, heel hook then go straight up
location: Same start for Sugar Mama and Sugar Bear

description: Start left of Sugar Butt. Go up to a crimp and a good mono, or skip the mono for a big move up to a good hold. Traverse into the finish of Sugar Butt
location: Left of the cave, left of Sugar Butt. Finishes on Sugar Butt

description: Start on Sweet Crack but instead of traversing left go straight up
location: Right of Sweet Crack

description: A traverse through almost all the problems in the cave that feels like a short 13d sport climb

Start on 2 sharp jugs in the right side of the cave, climb out of the cave to the start hold of Sugar Rush then traverse left. Either campus or heel hook your way into the start hold of Sugar Baby, then continue traversing up and left into the Sugar Daddy crimp rail. Go up with Right hand to a 3finger crimp, then move Left hand to the sharp crimp of Creme Brûlée and finish straight up on the slopers of Creme Brûlée.
location: Starts beneath Sugar Rush (right side of cave) and tops out on upper half of Creme Brûlée (left/middle part of the cave)
protection: Pads and spotters and emotional support staff

description: start on same underclings as Sugar Butt, move right hand into pinch and left hand crimp then make a wildly heinous move to a small sharp crimp up and right. One more hard move to a bad sloper side pull with left hand, then finish on better slopers and crimps to the top
location: Middle/left side of cave. Same start as Sugar Butt

parent_sector: Z. Bouldering in the Canyon Proper
description: The original start begins on two crimp side pulls, but the start holds and feet tend to be wet, so you may have to start in the next couple holds. Pull through the crimps into nice positive holds, then lean back on gastons. Then fight through slopers near the end.
location: O.B.D. Area (see Sandstone Warrior guide book for more details)

description: A Beautiful feature with some nice jugs. Start left where the bottom of the cliff meets the earth and work your way up and slightly right. Finish is the top of the rock.
location: This wall is a very distinct feature that should stand out. It should be one of the first things you see in the area. Rock is very red only on this wall. Right behind the large Green boulder.

description: This is one of the only actual boulders in the park suitable for climbing. This Green guy is coated in moss which is easy to clean off. The obvious line has been cleaned but may require touching up. Start low left and work your way over the bulge to top out.
location: This boulder is located in front of Red Rocket. It should stand out from far away as one of the largest and greenest boulders in the area. Boulder is about 20 feet in front of the cliffs. route is located on the river side of the boulder.

description: Stand start and work up.
location: Start in center of boulder.

description: Low sit start. Start on left side crimps and move up right toward lip.
location: The small overhang boulder directly on the other side of the trail from the railroad boulder.

parent_sector: Z. Bouldering in the Canyon Proper
description: Start on two small thunderclings with horrible feet, throw for the jug.  Traverse right and up through the jugs
location: Just south down the hill  of lovely tower, past the cool looking section with the horizontal seems.

parent_sector: Z. Bouldering in the Canyon Proper
description: Huge, grand, stunning. Walk your way up the perfect slab.
location: The huge boulder around the corner from Body Karate, about halfway down the canyon. Look for the massive, clean, sheer slabby face.
protection: No. Kind of a do not fall situation.

parent_sector: Z. Bouldering in the Canyon Proper
description: Start on the obvious jug and dyno to the chalked up sloper.
location: Can't remember exact location. Feel free to edit.

parent_sector: Z. Bouldering in the Canyon Proper
description: Fun little boulder problem! Sit start matched on rail, find feet and work your way up. Many variations exist. You can also work left onto the Arete which is fun as well. If there is another name for this please make the change. You can toss your shoes up and put them on, on top so you don’t have to walk through all the moss and mud.
location: About 100 yards past the Yosemite slab just off the trail on your left.

parent_sector: Z. Bouldering in the Canyon Proper
description: Begin matched on jug, do a few moves up on crimps, then left into the arête and up.
location: Reefer Madness Area (see Sandstone Warrior guide book for more details)

parent_sector: Z. Bouldering in the Canyon Proper
description: Start on crimps under the small roof, paste your feet and fire to the sloper lip. Establish your left hand on undercling, then try to figure out a way to mantle!
location: Creek Boulders (see Sandstone Warrior guide book for more details)
protection: Pads + Spotter (DON'T FALL INTO THE WATER)

parent_sector: Z. Bouldering in the Canyon Proper
description: Work your way up the right arête of the Yosemite slab.0
location: Right side of the Yosemite slab.

parent_sector: Z. Bouldering in the Canyon Proper
description: Sit start. Begin with left in positive pocket, your in one of the few shallow two finger pockets. Fire your way up to slopey crimps, then into the slopers at top. Fantastic mantle at top.
location: O.B.D. Area (see Sandstone Warrior guide book for more details)

parent_sector: Z. Bouldering in the Canyon Proper
description: A fun 5 move problem that starts on the upper portion of the rail. Starts on two crimps with the left foot pasted on the lower rail and the right foot heel hooked on the side of the boulder. Reach high left for good crimp. Switch feet onto the rail. Reach out right for sloper on right corner of the boulder. Heel hook up high left by left hand. Find right hand crimp on top and sloper on left and top out.
It's a fun short problem with the crux being the top out portion up the front of the boulder.
location: This problem is located in a large cave opening left of a small waterfall just past The Gallery with Battle Axe Tower slightly further down the trail.
protection: 1 crash pad will do. Two would be better.

parent_sector: Z. Bouldering in the Canyon Proper
description: Begin with a sit start under the the Body Karate boulder, throw to the lip and traverse right and finish on Body Karate.
location: Same boulder as Body Karate, but the side closer to Yosemite slab.

parent_sector: Z. Bouldering in the Canyon Proper
description: Start low on flake (same start as Berlier Problem), move up left.
location: Creek Boulders (see Sandstone Warrior guide book for more details)

parent_sector: Z. Bouldering in the Canyon Proper
description: Start with your left hand on undercling crimp, and your right hand undercling pinch. Establish feet, then catch crimp and finish.
location: Starts left side of the face that David and Goliath is on.

parent_sector: Z. Bouldering in the Canyon Proper
description: Start with left hand on a crimp side pull, right on lowest chalked ledge. Catch thumdercling, adjust and huck for the lip.
location: Starts on the right side of the face that Body Karate is on.

parent_sector: Z. Bouldering in the Canyon Proper
description: Just go straight up that corner from a sit start.
location: About 3 ft right of wolverine.

parent_sector: Z. Bouldering in the Canyon Proper
description: Start on slopers, travers right on arête then pull yourself over the lip.
location: Starts at the end of Body Karate and Hypoglycemia.

parent_sector: Z. Bouldering in the Canyon Proper
description: A powerful and beautiful roof compression problem. It starts with a couple of big throws, then some compression with tensiony, far away feet, and finishes with hero climbing on an awesome rail.
If you always wanted to climb The Vice, but don't climb v13 or can't get to Africa, this is your problem.
Arguably the best boulder problem in the canyon, and good enough that it stands out in the region.
Feels v9 to some body types.
location: This problem is located underneath the boulder just uphill from Yosemite Slab (v0-ish). Look for the steep compression problem leading to a beautiful finish rail.

Start on the undercling about 5 feet deep under the roof. There will be an obvious, left-facing foot rail. I started with my left hand in the good part, my right hand in the undercling that was left over, left toe in the foot rail, and shot right hand out to the rail.
protection: 2 big pads from Organic were perfect for us.

parent_sector: Z. Bouldering in the Canyon Proper
description: Start low, matched on flake, then move right to a juggy gaston, then pull up.
location: Creek Boulders (see Sandstone Warrior guide book for more details)

parent_sector: Z. Bouldering in the Canyon Proper
description: Start on two underclings. Work up through two finger pocket and sloped rail. Get to jug rail and finish by turning on to the slab to the right or left. Have fun!!
location: On the slightly overhung face of Yosemite Slab boulder facing the trail.
protection: Depends how confident you are on the slab top-out. 1-5 pads.

description: Move up steep terrain on nice holds to a dirty topout. From the starting holds, move up and right to the nice jug shelf, them work up left to the top.   Can be with a stand start when flooded.
location: Sit start on the far left side of the cave and move up obvious holds to the top.

description: A traverse from the right side of the cave to the top left. Crossover through shelves and jugs to the same topout as Warm Up v2. Can be done when flooded - just expect to get soaked if you fall!
location: Start on the far right side of the cave, traverse left and up to the same top out as Warm Up v2. Topout into bushes or drop from the top.

description: Start matched on good hold beneath the two big pockets and work up and left to a hang and drop
location: Located to the right of the Overlook wall

description: Needs some more cleaning and traffic on the boulder. Then, it will be a classic. Stand start and work straight up using the well-featured holds.
location: Right side of boulder.

description: Fun line.  Start on shelf and move through pockets, throw for the jug and top out.  Rinse and repeat.
Start matched on a huge ledge with small feet. Then move up and to the right to a crimp and a great jug. Then use another good hold on the top to move up the face.
location: Just to the right of Dream Crusher on the slab face.

description: Start in the big hole near the ground and work straight up using the crack
location: Starts to the left of Bane of Chris

description: This is a fun slab problem that starts on two small ledges with tiny variations in the rock for feet. Moving up to a sidepull and then manteling onto the top of the boulder is probably the crux. We climbed it in 90 degree weather. It is probably more of a 2 when it's cold out.
location: This route is on the freestanding boulder directly in front of the Alto Standard, is right on the trail. You'll find it on the left side of the slab close to the staircase.
protection: You might want a pad, but it's not that bad. Great landing.

description: Sit start and work up using the variety of well-featured holds.
location: Not actually on the railroad boulder, but directly across the trail from it on the face of the boulder facing toward the start of the trail.

description: Start on Kitten's Claws and work right using the underclings and top out on Bane of Chris
location: Same start as Kitten's Claws

description: Start standing with good holds and a massive pocket for a foot. Then use an undercling to reach up onto bulging face of the boulder and blindly find the crimp. Now match the crimp, hike up your feet, and then toss your left hand up to the ledge at the peak of the arete. Then get your feet up to the crimp and walk off the top.
location: The large overhanging bulge to the left of the slab face on the same boulder as Dream Crusher.

description: A neat addition right off the trail.
The obvious line traverses right  through the rail into the pocketed roof section and finishes with a good top out to the right.
It is a very obvious line, so I imagine that it has been climbed before.  Any Route name/ FA info?
location: The first left hand hallway encountered after carol lamb room.
Just before the stairway leading to the top of the cliff.
Starts down and to the left on an obvious low angled arete.

description: BEWARE THE PIKE!
This is a real bad boy.
You can identify by the pike shaped impression on the left of the route, and by the spike of doom below...
Moderately easy; a few little slopey holds/ insecure crimps.
Crux is a few committing moves leading to a scary and insecure topout.
Avoid choss to left and right of route. rock is solid in the middle.
BE ADVISED
There is a broken wooden post threatening to impale any would-be senders who happen to fall far enough to land on it. Fr tho stick a crash pad on it (or chop it down :).
Pro tip - go round and brush the top before topping out.
location: In Blue Elephant area (see Connor's Crack / Keaney's Wall for directions). From the crack, go around the north corner of the bluff until you come across a wall with a pike shaped impression on the wall, and a broken post in front of it. Route is on the right of the impression.

description: A little unnecessary but hey it's fun to spin around!

Start on the same holds as Reach Around, but go straight up the face without using any holds on the arete.  The crux involves rocking over your foot on a good foothold at the base of the head wall and balancing to stand up.  There is alot of growth on the face, but all the necessary holds are clean and not lost within the greenery.
location: Same start as Reach Around
protection: 1-2 pads.  Boulder is low to the ground but the landing is at 45 degrees or so.

description: Start climbing up the water groove. Do some long pulls on pockets. Interesting crux matching and moving off a not so great hold. Climbing gets easier after crux.
location: Located on the River wall. To the left of Float Trip and to the right of Egyptian Conniption. Shares the same start as Congo Spray, but heads right at the third bolt.

description: Climb up a face, through a small buldge, then up and right to the anchor
location: Only bolted route right of the waterfall.

description: This route starts on the left main face of the X Block and goes up the arete for 2 bolts. Then head left to finish up XOXO
location: Left side of X Block

description: Goes up the arete.
location: On the right arete of the south face of the X Block.

description: Great warm up for the harder routes in the area.  A little thin at the start and continuous.
location: Located just around the left arete of the south face of the X Block.
12 feet left of Xterminator (2nd route left on X Block).

description: Starts at the same point as "Slave Labor" and "Carpal Tunnel". Stay with the left line.
location: Mass Production wall. 20 feet left of "Assembly Line".

description: This route climbs up the dark streak slab. Probably also pretty dirty!
location: This route is directly to the right of the route “Delirious” on the other wall, and to the left of the route “Mystical Season”.

description: Seemingly impossible start leading up to some unique climbing on typical Jackson slab holds. Some may consider hard for the grade.
location: the first climb on the wall to the left of the belay ledge, left of team honda

description: Enjoy your ride up the wall on good positive holds.
location: Located directely to the right of “Killer Chickens” and to the left of “Spectator Sport”.

description: Start on small holds and move up the overhanging face with large holds and larger moves. Cruise the roof to the chains.
location: This route is down left and around the arete from fashionably late. The route is the just before the detached ledge.
protection: 7 bolts, 6 have fixed draws, 2 bolt chain anchor with fixed carabiners.

description: This route is tricky! Keep your eyes peeled for hidden holds.
location: Starts to the right of Four Bettys, and to the left of Three Day Impression.

description: Climb up the pocketed face.
location: This route is directly to the right of “Traffic Jam” and to the left of “Delirius”.

description: Starts at the same point as "Carpal Tunnel" and "Workshop". Veer right after first clip.
location: Mass Production wall. 20 feet left of "Assembly Line".

description: Climb up the bulging face.
location: Found on the Salemander Butteress. Found in between the routes “Gecko” on the left, and “Chameleon” on the right.

description: Climb up the sandy face. Don’t get tricked into going the wrong direction!
location: This is he last route on the right of the Salemander Buttress.

description: A neat boulder problem gets you to a steep roof. Move through the "Jackson Falls Jugs" in the roof to a deadpoint gaining the face and easier climbing to the anchors
location: On the left side of the section of the main wall that bulges out like some sort of pillar. Just right of Delirious.

description: Begin on the left Angelina crack, but cut right and follow the furthest right bolt line. The crux is between bolt 2 and 3. But it’s not over till you clip the chains.

Start with an interesting vertical crux to a good rest before big moves and sustained climbing through overhanging rock to hero jugs. A 13a variation goes up the arete to the right, bypassing the beginning crux. Listed as the Pipe Dream Project in Vertical Heartland.
location: On the right side of the overhanging main wall in front of the large spectator boulder

description: This ones a little thuggy, with a dynamic move for the crux. You end up linking up with Team Honda near the top.
location: The route directly to the right of Team Honda.

description: Shares the same start as “Hubba Hubba”, but you break left and follow the red streak at the 4th bolt.
location: Shares the same start as “Hubba Hubba”, break left at the 4th bolt. Found between “Pool of Reflection” on the right, and “Circle in the Round” on the left.

description: Tough climbing leads to a extremely severe crux. I’ve been told the crux sequence is about v10 alone. Luckily after the crux it’s gets significantly easier on he way to the chains.
location: The route with a couple perma draws directly to the right of “Float Trip”.

description: Start standing on the boulder to start the juggy traverse. The jugs run out when you pull yourself onto the head wall.
location: Begins on top of the boulder directly to the left of Balance of Power.

description: Climb the crack and either end at the anchors or top out through the right gully.
location: The middle of the wall to the left of Four Bettys Wall.

description: Climb up the left angling crack until I️t stops. Proceed to climb up the face.
location: Shares the same start as Poseur and Hoser.
protection: 8 bolts. Stick clip the first bolt

description: Climb up the left-facing flake until it runs out. Then move right and over the bulge.
location: This is the route closest to the arete on the left hand side of the wall. It can be found to the left of “Traffic Jam”.

description: Climb up the lime green streak near the gully.
location: The route directly to the right of “Jarred’s Route” and to the left of “Dupuy Conqueror”.

description: An interesting start leads to the first roof. Spend some time to figure out how to get in position to pull the roof. Don’t get comfortable! The climbing only gets harder for every bulge you pull.
location: The route directly to the right of “Remove La Ropa” and directly to the left of “Key Lime”.
